{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9faf67bf-3d76-4059-b42e-841eb9eb928e","content":"Here's the analysis and recommendations:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps a long-lived MSBuild server process in memory — no JIT, no assembly loading, no re-evaluation on each build.\n\n## Recommendations (in order of impact)\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\n\n.NET 8 supports an opt-in long-lived MSBuild server process, similar to what VS uses internally. Set this environment variable:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nThe first build pays normal startup cost; subsequent builds reuse the warm server — eliminating JIT and assembly-load overhead.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\n\nFor edit→build→test cycles, avoid spawning a new process entirely:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build          # rebuilds on file save\ndotnet watch run            # rebuilds and re-runs on file save\n```\n\nThis keeps the process alive and uses file-system watchers for near-instant incremental rebuilds.\n\n### 3. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is not disabled\n\nVerify this environment variable is **not** set to `1`:\n\n```bash\n# Bad — disables node reuse:\n# export MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1\n\n# Good — allow nodes to be reused (default):\nunset MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE\n```\n\n### 4. Use `-tl` (terminal logger) for perceived speed\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -tl\n```\n\nThe terminal logger reduces output noise and slightly reduces I/O overhead from console writes.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The project file itself is clean — this isn't a configuration issue. The 2–4 s overhead is inherent to cold-starting MSBuild per invocation. Enabling the **MSBuild Server** (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) is the single highest-impact change, bringing CLI no-op builds close to Visual Studio speeds.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7a6c866d-0559-4acd-9b1b-f1b72730af59","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` CLI builds are slow (2-4 seconds) even for no-op incremental builds, while Visual Studio rebuilds are nearly instant. They've ruled out analyzers and confirmed targets skip correctly. The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how Visual Studio and the CLI handle builds:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** keeps an MSBuild server process running in the background, so it doesn't pay the startup cost each time.\n2. **`dotnet build`** by default launches a new MSBuild process each time, which includes JIT compilation, loading assemblies, and evaluating the project graph.\n\n\n3. **MSBuild Server** (.NET 8+) can be enabled with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` to keep MSBuild nodes alive between builds, eliminating the startup penalty.\n\nThe main recommendations are to enable the MSBuild Server feature to match Visual Studio's behavior, or use `dotnet watch` for continuous development workflows where the process stays resident. The key actionable items are enabling the MSBuild Server with the environment variable to avoid repeated JIT and assembly loading overhead, and using `dotnet watch` for the development loop to keep the process alive between builds rather than spawning new ones each time.","outputTokens":1395,"requestId":"1415:16A6CA:DEC57EA:F7F9BCC:69EC0E7C"},"id":"19cc3ddc-a573-4808-a8a9-5ad5da5fba5a","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:45:12.883Z","parentId":"04c4c9f7-89a0-46a9-b919-1e3e0d7a7294"}
